However, while most women do not receive knowledge about or support for abortion, they can access termination of pregnancy in Rwanda. Abortion is legal in Rwanda if there is reasonable evidence that carrying the pregnancy may lead to harm to the woman’s life, physical or mental health, or other danger to the survival of the fetus (United Nations Population Fund, 2009). In Rwanda, abortion is most often performed in health facilities by a trained midlevel health professional, such as a nurse or midwife, as in the rest of the Sub-Saharan Africa. However, women can also access surgical abortions under a legal medical indications in private health facilities run by nongovernmental organizations despite local laws being more conservative in this regard. Through heavy investments in the medical infrastructure, health-care providers in Rwanda are able to provide surgical abortions within existing health facilities (Gottlieb & Binder, 2008).

Study design

A retrospective study of women who were enrolled into a tuberculosis diagnosis, treatment and prevention program in Rwanda was conducted. The aim of the program was to determine the frequency of women in the antenatal care program who wanted to terminate their pregnancies with a trained health-care worker through medication method during the three (or more) gestational days (Crawshaw,Thein Han,Oba,Prasad, & Collins, 2001).
